<p class="body">Processing is the step between the coffee farm and the roaster, and it is the most underappreciated variable in coffee flavor. Two coffees from the same farm, grown from the same variety in the same soil, processed differently will taste like different coffees. The cherry fruit that surrounds the coffee bean contains sugars, acids, and microorganisms that interact with the bean during processing, and how long and in what form that interaction continues determines more about the final cup than most buyers realize.</p>

<p class="body">There are five processing methods worth understanding. Three are primary and established: washed, natural, and honey. Two are more recent or regionally specific: anaerobic fermentation and wet-hulled (Giling Basah), the Indonesian method that produces Sumatra's distinctive character. Each method is covered step by step below, with the cup profile it produces and specific coffees to buy to experience it.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Washed Processing: <em>Terroir in the Cup</em></h2>

<p class="body">Washed processing, also called wet processing or fully washed, is the dominant method in Ethiopia, Kenya, Colombia, Central America, and many other specialty-forward origins. Its defining characteristic is that the fruit is removed before the coffee dries, so the bean dries clean, and whatever flavor comes through is largely a product of the variety, soil, and altitude rather than the fruit itself.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">The Washed Process, Step by Step</h3>
<ul class="body-list">
  <li>Ripe cherries are harvested and sorted, typically by density floatation to remove underripe or defective fruit.</li>
  <li>The skin and pulp are removed by a pulping machine, usually within 24 to 36 hours of picking to prevent unwanted fermentation on the skin.</li>
  <li>The depulped coffee still has a sticky mucilage layer clinging to it. This mucilage is removed through controlled fermentation: the coffee sits in fermentation tanks or channels, usually with water, for 12 to 72 hours depending on temperature and altitude.</li>
  <li>After fermentation, the coffee is thoroughly washed with clean water to remove any remaining mucilage.</li>
  <li>The clean, parchment-covered coffee is dried on raised beds or patio surfaces, typically for two to four weeks, until it reaches 10 to 12 percent moisture content.</li>
  <li>The dried parchment is removed (milled), and the green coffee is sorted, graded, and bagged for export.</li>
</ul>

<p class="body">The cup profile of well-executed washed coffee is characterized by clarity. The dominant flavors come from the coffee's variety and growing environment: the jasmine and bergamot of Ethiopian Yirgacheffe, the blackcurrant of Kenyan SL28, the stone fruit and citrus of Colombian Huila. Acidity is typically bright and clean rather than fruit-driven. Body ranges from light to medium. There is a transparency to washed coffees that lets a taster follow a clear thread from origin to cup.</p>

<p class="body">The risk in washed processing is in the fermentation step. Under-fermentation leaves mucilage residue that can create an unpleasant soapy quality. Over-fermentation produces a harsh, vinegar-like defect. The best washed coffees come from producers with rigorous fermentation control: consistent temperature, monitored pH, and clean water throughout.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <p>Ethiopian Yirgacheffe washed is the single clearest example of what washed processing achieves at its best. Jasmine, bergamot, stone fruit, tea-like body: a cup that reads like a window into the specific altitude and soil of southern Ethiopia. If you have never experienced a great washed Ethiopian, it is the logical first step in understanding what coffee flavor actually is.</p>
</div>

