<h2 class="section-head">Natural Processing: <em>The Fruit Does the Work</em></h2>

<p class="body">Natural processing, also called dry processing, is the oldest method in coffee and the one most likely to produce either the most exciting or the most problematic cup, depending on the quality of execution. In natural processing, the whole coffee cherry is dried intact, fruit and all, and the bean inside absorbs flavor from the fermenting fruit over a period of weeks.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">The Natural Process, Step by Step</h3>
<ul class="body-list">
  <li>Ripe cherries are harvested, often sorted by density floatation to remove anything underdeveloped.</li>
  <li>The whole cherries, unpulped and unprocessed, are spread on raised drying beds or patios in thin layers.</li>
  <li>Workers rake or turn the cherries regularly (typically several times per day) to prevent mold and ensure even drying.</li>
  <li>The cherries dry slowly over three to six weeks in open air, during which the fruit sugars and acids permeate the coffee bean through osmotic and fermentative processes.</li>
  <li>Once the dried cherries reach roughly 11 to 12 percent moisture, they are hulled (the dried fruit and parchment are removed at once), and the green coffee is sorted and prepared for export.</li>
</ul>

<p class="body">The cup profile of a well-executed natural is unmistakable: blueberry, strawberry, cherry, dark stone fruit, and a full, almost syrupy body. The fruit flavors are often dramatically more present than in washed coffees from the same origin, because the bean has been soaking in the fermenting cherry for weeks. This effect is so pronounced that inexperienced tasters sometimes suspect the coffee has been flavored artificially. It has not; the fruit compounds are naturally occurring.</p>

<p class="body">The risk in natural processing is significant. If the cherries are not turned regularly, or if the drying environment has too much humidity or inconsistent airflow, uneven fermentation produces defects: sour ferment, vinegar, alcohol, and "barnyard" off-flavors. The difference between a spectacular natural and a defective one is largely about the producer's rigor during the drying period.</p>

<p class="body">Ethiopia produces the world's most celebrated naturals, particularly from Yirgacheffe and Guji zones. Harrar's dry-processed lots have been around for centuries and represent a different, wilder style of natural with wine-like complexity. Brazil also produces naturals extensively, though at generally lower elevation and with less aromatic complexity than Ethiopian examples.</p>

