<h2 class="section-head">Honey Processing: <em>Between Clean and Fruity</em></h2>

<p class="body">Honey processing is a hybrid that occupies the middle ground between washed and natural, and it is one of the most versatile and interesting methods in specialty coffee. Like washed processing, the cherry skin is removed first. Unlike washed, the sticky mucilage layer is not washed away: it is left on the bean during drying, where it ferments slowly and contributes sweetness and fruit complexity to the final cup.</p>

<p class="body">The term honey does not refer to the flavor of honey or any added ingredient. It refers to the sticky, honey-like quality of the mucilage layer itself. Costa Rica is credited with systematizing and naming the honey process categories that are now used industry-wide.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Yellow, Red, and Black Honey</h3>
<p class="body"><strong>Yellow honey</strong> leaves roughly 25 percent of the mucilage on the bean and dries quickly, typically over one to two weeks in good weather. The cup effect is subtle: slightly more body and stone fruit sweetness than a fully washed coffee from the same origin, with less of the fruity intensity of a natural. It is often described as the most approachable honey process because it is closest to what washed drinkers expect.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Red honey</strong> leaves approximately 50 percent of the mucilage and takes two to three weeks to dry. The additional mucilage requires more careful turning and management to prevent uneven fermentation. The cup shows more pronounced stone fruit, peach, and apricot notes, with medium-full body and sweetness that bridges the gap between washed clarity and natural fruit intensity. This is the most commonly produced honey grade at quality-focused farms.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Black honey</strong> leaves 100 percent of the mucilage intact and dries for up to six weeks in controlled conditions. This is the most labor-intensive honey variation and the closest to natural processing in final cup character: tropical fruit, deep sweetness, syrupy body, and a complexity that takes longer to dial in on the roaster. Black honey coffees from producers who execute it well are some of the most distinctive and sought-after coffees in the specialty market.</p>

