<h2 class="section-head">Anaerobic Processing: <em>The New Frontier</em></h2>

<p class="body">Anaerobic coffee processing entered the specialty mainstream in the 2010s, driven by competition baristas looking for unusual and memorable cup profiles for world barista championship sets. It has since become a legitimate production method at farms that have invested in the infrastructure to do it consistently.</p>

<p class="body">In anaerobic processing, coffee cherries or depulped coffee are placed in sealed stainless steel tanks with oxygen evacuated and replaced with CO2, or simply sealed to allow natural CO2 buildup from fermentation. The absence of oxygen creates a fundamentally different fermentation environment from the aerobic (oxygen-present) fermentation that happens in traditional washed or natural processing.</p>

<p class="body">The anaerobic environment encourages lactic acid bacteria and specific yeast strains that do not thrive in aerobic conditions. These microorganisms produce unusual flavor compounds: tropical fruit notes like passion fruit, mango, and guava; wine-like qualities; spiced notes of cinnamon, clove, and rum; and in the most extreme examples, a distilled-spirit quality that reads almost more like a cocktail ingredient than a coffee. Temperature control during anaerobic fermentation is critical: higher temperatures accelerate the process but can push the flavors into undesirable territory.</p>

<p class="body">Anaerobic processing is the most divisive in specialty coffee. Enthusiasts love the intensity and novelty of the flavors produced, which are unlike anything from traditional processing methods. Critics argue that the processing overwrites terroir, making a Kenyan anaerobic taste more like "anaerobic character" than like Kenya. Both observations are accurate. Whether you consider that a feature or a bug depends on what you value in coffee.</p>

<p class="body">For buyers exploring new experiences, anaerobic coffees are best approached with expectations calibrated to the unusual: these are not gateway coffees. For the buyer who has tasted washed and natural and honey and wants to push further, an anaerobic from a skilled producer is one of the most memorable things in the specialty world. For the buyer who just wants a good morning cup, it is likely more intensity than they are looking for.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Wet-Hulled (Giling Basah): <em>The Indonesian Method</em></h2>

<p class="body">Wet-hulling, known locally as Giling Basah in Indonesian, is the processing method almost entirely responsible for the distinctive character of Sumatran coffee and, to a lesser degree, coffees from Sulawesi and Flores. Understanding it explains why Indonesian coffees taste so different from everything else in the specialty world, and why they taste that way consistently across decades of production.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">The Wet-Hull Process, Step by Step</h3>
<ul class="body-list">
  <li>Ripe cherries are picked and pulped to remove the skin, typically within a day.</li>
  <li>The pulped coffee undergoes a short fermentation period, usually eight to twelve hours, to loosen the remaining mucilage.</li>
  <li>The coffee is washed and then partially dried on patios or raised beds while still in its parchment layer, until it reaches approximately 30 to 35 percent moisture content. Standard washed coffees dry to below 12 percent before hulling; Giling Basah stops here.</li>
  <li>The still-moist parchment is removed in a wet-hulling machine. This is the key step: the parchment comes off while the bean inside still has elevated moisture, exposing the green bean to the environment at a vulnerable stage.</li>
  <li>The exposed, still-moist green coffee is laid out to finish drying without its parchment protection. During this final drying, the bean absorbs flavor from the air and the drying surface, and continues to develop in a different way than a parchment-covered bean would.</li>
</ul>

<p class="body">The cup result is a distinctively earthy, herbal, full-bodied coffee with low acidity. Dark chocolate, cedar, tobacco, mushroom, and forest floor notes are common. Body is typically heavy. The flavor compounds produced by wet-hulling are so characteristic that experienced tasters can identify Sumatran coffee blind. Defects are also common in wet-hulled coffees because the exposed drying stage creates more opportunities for contamination, but quality-focused producers who control this step carefully produce remarkably consistent, deeply satisfying cups.</p>

<p class="body">Wet-hulled coffees respond unusually well to darker roast levels. Unlike washed Ethiopian or Kenyan coffees, which lose their defining character under dark roasting, Sumatran coffees often reveal more complexity when taken to a true medium-dark. The earthiness and body that characterize the origin suit extended roast development.</p>

