<h2 class="section-head">Choosing by <em>Processing Method</em></h2>

<p class="body">If you are buying single-origin coffee and trying to match your purchase to what you like, the processing method is often a more useful filter than the origin. Here is a straightforward decision framework.</p>

<p class="body">Buy washed if you want: clean cups, bright acidity, terroir-forward flavor, consistent quality that is less dependent on the producer's drying conditions, and a profile that rewards pour-over brewing and light-to-medium roasting. Washed coffees from Ethiopia, Kenya, and Colombia are the entry points for most serious coffee drinkers.</p>

<p class="body">Buy natural if you want: intense fruit flavor, heavy body, jam-like sweetness, a cup that surprises people who think they know what coffee tastes like. Natural coffees from Ethiopia and Brazil are the most accessible starting points. Be aware that quality execution varies significantly and defective naturals are more common than defective washed coffees.</p>

<p class="body">Buy honey if you want: the middle ground. Stone fruit, peach, apricot, syrupy sweetness with more body than washed but more control than natural. Costa Rican honeys are the benchmark. Red honey is the most balanced entry point.</p>

<p class="body">Buy anaerobic if you want: maximum novelty, tropical fruit complexity, and flavors that do not resemble anything from traditional coffee. Best for experienced specialty drinkers or events where you want to create a memorable impression. Be ready for something that challenges expectations.</p>

<p class="body">Buy wet-hulled (Sumatra) if you want: full body, low acidity, earthy complexity, and a coffee that works well dark-roasted, in milk, or as an espresso base. Sumatran coffees are the best single-origin recommendation for customers who drink espresso with milk.</p>

